<p>We primarily assess the quality of predictions in terms of mean absolute error (MAE). Given a set of 
 <italic>N</italic> true outcomes, 
 <italic>y</italic>, and corresponding predictions, 
 <inline-formula id="pcbi.1005248.e001">
  <alternatives>
   <graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1005248.e001.jpg" id="pcbi.1005248.e001g" mimetype="image" position="anchor" orientation="portrait" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
   <math id="M1">
    <mover accent="true">
     <mi>y</mi>
     <mo>^</mo>
    </mover>
   </math>
  </alternatives>
 </inline-formula>, MAE can be written as: 
 <disp-formula id="pcbi.1005248.e002">
  <alternatives>
   <graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1005248.e002.jpg" id="pcbi.1005248.e002g" mimetype="image" position="anchor" orientation="portrait" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
   <math id="M2">
    <mrow>
     <mtext>MAE</mtext>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mn>1</mn>
      <mi>N</mi>
     </mfrac>
     <munderover>
      <mo>∑</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mi>i</mi>
       <mo>=</mo>
       <mn>1</mn>
      </mrow>
      <mi>N</mi>
     </munderover>
     <mo>∣</mo>
     <msub>
      <mi>y</mi>
      <mi>i</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>-</mo>
     <msub>
      <mover accent="true">
       <mi>y</mi>
       <mo>^</mo>
      </mover>
      <mi>i</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>∣</mo>
     <mtext>.</mtext>
    </mrow>
   </math>
  </alternatives>
 </disp-formula>
</p>
